Opioids in Virginia¶

Question 1¶

Do opioid overdoses tend to be associated with less affluent areas; that is, areas where families have lower incomes?

In [2]:
#Import the OpiodsVA.csv file
df_op = pd.read_csv('OpioidsVA.csv')

#Create grid for plots
gridsize = (3, 2)

#Create subplots
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (15, 20)) #Set figure size
ax1 = plt.subplot2grid(gridsize, (0, 0), colspan = 2, rowspan = 2) #Set first graph in grid
ax2 = plt.subplot2grid(gridsize, (2, 0)) #Set second graph in grid
ax3 = plt.subplot2grid(gridsize, (2, 1)) #Set third graph in grid
fig.suptitle('Opioid Overdoses vs. Median Household Income', fontsize = 20) #Figure title

#Create scatterplots
"""A scatterplot was chosen to compare the relationship between rates of total opioid deaths and median household income;
rx opioid and fentanyl & heroin overdoses are both included as they both meet the definition of opioids."""
df1 = df_op[['MedianHouseholdIncome', 'FPOO-Rate', 'FFHO-Rate']].copy() #Create a df for both OD rates
df1 = df1[df1['FPOO-Rate'] + df1['FFHO-Rate'] > 0] #Eliminate all zero rows
ax1.scatter(df1['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df1['FPOO-Rate'] + df1['FFHO-Rate'], alpha = 0.5, c = 'g') #Scatterplot for total ODs
a, b = np.polyfit(df1['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df1["FPOO-Rate"] + df1['FFHO-Rate'], deg = 1) #Fit linear trend
est = a * df1['MedianHouseholdIncome'] + b #Linear trend line
ax1.plot(df1['MedianHouseholdIncome'], est, 'r--') #Plot trend line
ax1.set_title('Total Opioid Overdoses') #Graph title
ax1.xaxis.set_label_text('Median Household Income') #X-axis caption
ax1.yaxis.set_label_text('Overdoses') #Y-axis caption

"""A scatterplot was chosen to compare the relationship between rates of fentanyl & heroin opioid deaths and
median household income."""
df2 = df_op[['MedianHouseholdIncome', 'FFHO-Rate']].copy() #Create a df for fentanyl & heroin OD rates
df2 = df2[df2['FFHO-Rate'] > 0] #Eliminate zero rows
ax2.scatter(df2['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df2['FFHO-Rate'], alpha = 0.5, c = 'b') #Scatterplot for FHODs
a, b = np.polyfit(df2['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df2['FFHO-Rate'], deg = 1) #Fit linear trend
est = a * df2['MedianHouseholdIncome'] + b #Linear trend line
ax2.plot(df2['MedianHouseholdIncome'], est, 'r--') #Plot trend line
ax2.set_title('Fentanyl & Heroin Overdoses') #Graph title
ax2.xaxis.set_label_text('Median Household Income') #X-axis caption
ax2.yaxis.set_label_text('Overdoses') #Y-axis caption

"""A scatterplot was chosen to compare the relationship between rates of prescription opioid deaths and
median household income."""
df3 = df_op[['MedianHouseholdIncome', 'FPOO-Rate']].copy() #Create a df for rx opioid OD rates
df3 = df3[df3['FPOO-Rate'] > 0] #Eliminate zero rows
ax3.scatter(df3['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df3['FPOO-Rate'], alpha = 0.5, c = 'y') #Scatterplot for POODs
a, b = np.polyfit(df3['MedianHouseholdIncome'], df3["FPOO-Rate"], deg = 1) #Fit linear trend
est = a * df3['MedianHouseholdIncome'] + b #linear trend line
ax3.plot(df3['MedianHouseholdIncome'], est, 'r--') #Plot trend line
ax3.set_title('Prescription Opioid Overdoses') # Graph title
ax3.xaxis.set_label_text('Median Household Income') #X-axis caption
ax3.yaxis.set_label_text('Overdoses'); #Y-axis caption

Median household income and opioid overdoses demonstrate slight negative correlation; the effect is less pronounced for fentanyl and heroin overdoses.

Question 2¶

Some people who start with [prescription] opioid addictions are reported to transition to heroin [opiate/opioid] use. What is the relationship in Virginia counties between [prescription] opioid overdoses and heroin [opiate/opioid] overdoses?

In [3]:
#Create subplots
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.suptitle('Prescription Opioid Overdoses vs. Fentanyl & Heroin Overdoses', fontsize = 20) #Figure title
fig.set_size_inches(15, 8) #Set figure size

"""A scatterplot was chosen to compare the relationship between rates of prescription opioid deaths and fentanyl
& heroin opioid deaths."""
df4 = df_op[['FFHO-Rate', 'FPOO-Rate']].copy() #Create a df for both OD rates
df4 = df4[df4['FPOO-Rate'] > 0] #Eliminate zero rows
df4 = df4[df4['FFHO-Rate'] > 0] #Eliminate zero rows
ax.scatter(df4['FFHO-Rate'], df4['FPOO-Rate'], alpha = 0.5, c = 'tab:brown') #Scatterplot for both OD rates
a, b = np.polyfit(df4['FFHO-Rate'], df4["FPOO-Rate"], deg = 1) #Fit linear trend
est = a * df4['FFHO-Rate'] + b #Linear trend line
ax.plot(df4['FFHO-Rate'], est, 'r--') #Plot trend line
ax.xaxis.set_label_text('Fentanyl & Heroin Overdose Rate') #X-axis caption
ax.yaxis.set_label_text('Prescription Opioid Overdose Rate'); #Y-axis caption

Postive correlation is observed between prescription opioid overdoses and overdoses of fentanyl and heroin; greater numbers of one overdose type are associated with greater numbers of the other.

Presidents¶

Question 1¶

Which states are associated with the greatest number of United States presidents in terms of the presidents' birthplaces?

In [4]:
#Import the presidents.csv file
df_pres = pd.read_csv('presidents.csv')

States = np.unique(df_pres['State']) #See unique state values
Count = df_pres['State'].value_counts() #Count the number of unique state values

#Create figure subplots
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(20, 8) #Set figure size
fig.suptitle('U.S. Presidents\' Birthplace by State', fontsize = 20) #Figure title

"""A bar plot was chosen to demonstrate the counts of each unique state by president birthplace; color and hatching employed
to make the graph a bit fun but wouldn't be used for a formal presentation."""
Count.plot.bar(edgecolor = ['none', 'black', 'none'], color = ['red', 'white', 'blue'], hatch = '*') #Bar plot of state frequency
ax.set_xticklabels(labels = Count.index, rotation = 45)
ax.yaxis.set_label_text('Number of U.S. Presidents Born in State', fontsize = 14) #X-axis caption
ax.xaxis.set_label_text('States of U.S. President Birth', fontsize = 14); #Y-axis caption

Virginia is the birthplace of the highest number of U.S. presidents, with eight having been born there; Ohio, New York, and Massachusetts follow with seven, five, and four, respectively.

U.S. Monthly Auto Sales¶

Question 1¶

How have vehicle sales in the United States varied over time?

In [5]:
#Import the TOTALNSA.csv file
df_auto = pd.read_csv('TOTALNSA.csv')
df_auto['DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(df_auto['DATE']) #Convert date to datetime

#Create figure subplots
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(30, 15) #Set figure size
fig.suptitle('U.S. Monthly Auto Sales', fontsize = 20) #Figure title

"""A line graph was chosen to present the data because it is a time series."""
plt.plot(df_auto['DATE'], df_auto['TOTALNSA']) #Line graph of monthly auto sales
plt.figtext(0.8, 0.25, df_auto['TOTALNSA'].describe().to_string(), fontsize = 14)
ax.yaxis.set_label_text('Number of Monthly Auto Sales', fontsize = 14) #X-axis caption
ax.xaxis.set_label_text('Time', fontsize = 14); #Y-axis caption

U.S. monthly auto sales have varied substantially over time (likely corresponding with macroeconomic and seasonal trends), with a minimum of 670, maximum of 1845, and standard deviation of 225.
